3. The Story Stack

No one inhabits only one narrative.

An individual may simultaneously execute:

family story
national story
religious story
career story
gender story
economic story
romantic story
personal mythology
platform-generated story
momentary emotional story

Let the active narrative state be:

\mathcal{N}_t = \{N_1, N_2, \ldots, N_k\}

Each narrative has a current influence weight:

w_i(t) \geq 0

The agent’s interpretation of an event x_t can be represented as:

z_t = \sum_{i=1}^{k} w_i(t)\phi_i(x_t)

where:

* x_t is the observed event,
* \phi_i is the interpretation produced by narrative N_i,
* w_i(t) is that narrative’s current authority,
* z_t is the combined perceived meaning.

The resulting action is selected through a policy:

a_t \sim \pi(a \mid z_t, m_t, s_t)

where:

* m_t is memory,
* s_t is internal state,
* \pi is the behavioral policy.

This explains why behavior cannot be understood by looking only at external circumstances.

The agent is not reacting only to reality.

The agent is reacting to reality after it has passed through a layered narrative compiler.

