5. Method Acting as Deliberate Runtime Selection

Method acting in real life can be interpreted as intentional policy modulation.

Instead of asking:

What would I normally do?

the agent asks:

What would this character notice?
What would this role permit?
What action would preserve this story?
What emotional state would make that action natural?

Formally, the agent swaps or modifies its policy:

\pi_{\text{default}}
\rightarrow
\pi_{\text{role}}

This is not necessarily deception.

It can be controlled identity exploration.

class RoleRuntime:
    def __init__(self, values, attention_bias, action_rules):
        self.values = values
        self.attention_bias = attention_bias
        self.action_rules = action_rules
    def render(self, observation):
        noticed = self.attention_bias(observation)
        return choose_action(noticed, self.values, self.action_rules)

A role changes what becomes salient before it changes behavior.

The warrior sees threats.

The comedian sees incongruity.

The entrepreneur sees unmet demand.

The artist sees composition.

The absurdist sees where the rules reveal their own arbitrariness.

Thus:

A role is an attention filter before it is a costume.

