8. AI as Narrative Compiler

A language model can be interpreted as a narrative compiler.

It receives:

prompt
+ context
+ training patterns
+ system constraints
+ conversational history

It then generates the most coherent continuation available under those conditions.

y_{1:T} \sim P(y_{1:T} \mid x, c, \theta)

But the crucial question is not only:

What text will the model produce?

It is:

What world does the prompt cause the model to inhabit?
What role has the model been assigned?
Which narrative rules are active?
What continuation becomes locally inevitable?

Prompting is therefore a form of runtime construction.

prompt = {
    "world": world_model,
    "role": assigned_role,
    "objective": desired_outcome,
    "constraints": boundaries,
    "memory": relevant_history,
    "style": expression_interface
}

A powerful prompt does not merely request output.

It constructs the stage from which the output becomes natural.

Prompt engineering is narrative environment design.

