10. Narrative Attention

Stories do more than explain events.

They allocate attention.

Let the environment contain features:

X = \{x_1, x_2, \ldots, x_n\}

A narrative applies an attention mask:

\alpha_i = P(x_i \text{ is relevant} \mid N)

The perceived world becomes:

\tilde{X}_N = \{\alpha_1x_1, \alpha_2x_2, \ldots, \alpha_nx_n\}

Different stories make different features visible.

An investor sees cash flow.

A detective sees inconsistencies.

A child sees play.

A soldier sees terrain.

A poet sees metaphor.

An AI trained to switch narrative lenses gains access to multiple salience maps over the same reality.

def multi_lens_analysis(event, lenses):
    return {
        lens.name: lens.attend(event)
        for lens in lenses
    }

This is not only stylistic variation.

It is computational diversity.

A new story can reveal new data without changing the underlying scene.

