11. Narrative Geometry

A story can also be modeled as a trajectory through state space.

Let s_t be the world-state.

s_{t+1} = F(s_t, a_t, \epsilon_t)

A plot is a path:

\gamma = (s_0, s_1, \ldots, s_T)

A compelling story gives the path structure:

* direction,
* tension,
* thresholds,
* reversals,
* attractors,
* forbidden regions,
* terminal states.

A goal narrative introduces an attractor g:

\lim_{t \to T} d(s_t, g) \rightarrow 0

A tragedy may contain an attractor the character cannot perceive.

A redemption arc changes the transition function.

A comedy collapses an assumed distance between incompatible states.

An absurdist work exposes that the coordinate system itself was invented.

