13. Narrative Gradient Descent

Learning can be modeled as iterative adjustment of the story governing action.

Let the agent possess narrative parameters \theta.

After an outcome produces loss L:

\theta_{t+1}
=
\theta_t
-
\eta \nabla_\theta L

But humans do not update only from raw error.

They update according to the explanation assigned to the error.

\theta_{t+1}
=
\theta_t
-
\eta \nabla_\theta L
+
\lambda R(N_t)

where R(N_t) represents narrative interpretation.

The same failure can update the agent toward:

avoidance
resentment
curiosity
discipline
humility
experimentation

Therefore the quality of the learning update depends partly on the narrative attached to the result.

Experience supplies the gradient. Story determines what gets updated.

